entation of the value they place on their workforce. Consider the subconscious impact of producing mandatory, low quality, poorly designed material. What does that say to your team? Why should they engage with the content?\r\n\r\nIn short, treat online learning with the same respect of creative treatment that you would if you were producing a marketing piece for Google themselves. Make it stand out, make it different, be creative.\r\n\r\nThis playful approach is something that we fully embrace at Tilt. Our mantra to learning is simple, pay attention to how and what users interact with online in their spare time, then use this to help shape workplace digital experiences.\r\n\r\nOne example of this, was a challenge a client faced in how best to educate and support new leaders around the importance of non-verbal communication within their team.\r\n\r\nThe obvious choice for explaining non verbal cues was for users to see it in action, and so we decided to produce a series of films to showcase these. The use of film in learning content is nothing new, so why use this as an example?\r\n\r\nWe worked with the Royal Academy of Dramatic Arts (RADA) ‘In Business’ team, to provide talented actors to help bring to life the subtle non verbal cues and tone of voice that form the majority of team interactions in the workplace. Each film illustrated a leadership scenario in a quirky, real-world vignette that a newly transition leader could related to. The assistance of RADA helped add a level of gravitas and understanding to the messaging, whilst at the same time maintaining the users attention through a light hearted style and quality production values.\r\n\r\nBy pairing emotive, engaging rich media content with direct, practical information, we helped our intended audience enjoy the experience and retain the information.\r\n\r\n\"These videos smashed all previous records – for click-through’s and video plays – doubling the previous highest ever. Congrats.\"\r\nShane Samarawikrema, BP\r\n\r\nFor more information about these videos and the wider project, please visit: <a href=\"http://wearetilt.com/work/bp-fll/\">http://wearetilt.com/work/bp-fll/</a>\r\n'),(7511,683,'_main_content_area','field_5629ec918a334'),(7514,684,'header_image','672'),(7515,684,'_header_image','field_5629edc6a3424'),(7516,684,'standfirst_text','Good stories make you feel and think; the same should be true for online learning. As our digital world evolves, our online experiences become ever more immersive, designed to illicit emotion and draw users in. These experiences set a level of expectation that our audiences demand; a new status quo that increases year on year.'),(7517,684,'_standfirst_text','field_5629ea6d8d729'),(7518,684,'image_1','679'),(7519,684,'_image_1','field_560ba235a1f37'),(7520,684,'image_2','680'),(7521,684,'_image_2','field_560ba25da1f38'),(7522,684,'image_3','681'),(7523,684,'_image_3','field_560ba272a1f39'),(7524,684,'image_4','682'),(7525,684,'_image_4','field_560ba279a1f3a'),(7526,684,'single_image',''),(7527,684,'_single_image','field_5629ea2db47b2'),(7528,684,'vimeo_id',''),(7529,684,'_vimeo_id','field_5629e91cf9252'),(7530,684,'vimeo_id_two',''),(7531,684,'_vimeo_id_two','field_564b0ac8ebbf4'),(7532,684,'youtube_id',''),(7533,684,'_youtube_id','field_5629e94ef9253'),(7534,684,'_','field_5629e968f9254'),(7535,684,'main_content_area','Why then, do we still see prosaic learning content being produced where the experience is considered secondary to the subject matter being delivered?\r\n\r\nProducing learning content with the same love, passion and enthusiasm that we see injected into customer facing experiences is essential to its success. Better still, as content creators, we have the opportunity & responsibility, to add a little “surprise and delight” into our audiences learning experiences, by curating something a little unexpected.\r\n\r\n‘Enjoyment’, ‘surprise’, ‘delight’, ‘unexpected’, are you ‘engaged’ yet?\r\n\r\nInstead, we still see fo