8a334'),(7774,704,'header_image','672'),(7775,704,'_header_image','field_5629edc6a3424'),(7776,704,'standfirst_text','Good stories make you feel and think; the same should be true for online learning. As our digital world evolves, our online experiences become ever more immersive, designed to illicit emotion and draw users in. These experiences set a level of expectation that our audiences demand; a new status quo that increases year on year.'),(7777,704,'_standfirst_text','field_5629ea6d8d729'),(7778,704,'image_1','679'),(7779,704,'_image_1','field_560ba235a1f37'),(7780,704,'image_2','680'),(7781,704,'_image_2','field_560ba25da1f38'),(7782,704,'image_3','681'),(7783,704,'_image_3','field_560ba272a1f39'),(7784,704,'image_4','682'),(7785,704,'_image_4','field_560ba279a1f3a'),(7786,704,'single_image',''),(7787,704,'_single_image','field_5629ea2db47b2'),(7788,704,'vimeo_id',''),(7789,704,'_vimeo_id','field_5629e91cf9252'),(7790,704,'vimeo_id_two',''),(7791,704,'_vimeo_id_two','field_564b0ac8ebbf4'),(7792,704,'youtube_id',''),(7793,704,'_youtube_id','field_5629e94ef9253'),(7794,704,'_','field_5629e968f9254'),(7795,704,'main_content_area','Why then, do we still see prosaic learning content being produced where the experience is considered secondary to the subject matter being delivered?\r\n\r\nProducing learning content with the same love, passion and enthusiasm that we see injected into customer facing experiences is essential to its success. Better still, as content creators, we have the opportunity & responsibility, to add a little “surprise and delight” into our audiences learning experiences, by curating something a little unexpected.\r\n\r\n‘Enjoyment’, ‘surprise’, ‘delight’, ‘unexpected’, are you ‘engaged’ yet?\r\n\r\nInstead, we still see focus being poured into the subject matter only, relying on templated content management systems to serve out and track employee compliance. It might be easy, but will it deliver results? Will your employees actually enjoy the experience, engage with content and finally, retain the information?\r\n\r\nA company’s learning strategy to an employee is a window into the soul of the company itself. It’s a representation of the value they place on their workforce. Consider the subconscious impact of producing mandatory, low quality, poorly designed material. What does that say to your team? Why should they engage with the content?\r\n\r\nIn short, treat online learning with the same respect of creative treatment that you would if you were producing a marketing piece for Google themselves. Make it stand out, make it different, be creative.\r\n\r\nThis playful approach is something that we fully embrace at Tilt. Our mantra to learning is simple, pay attention to how and what users interact with online in their spare time, then use this to help shape workplace digital experiences.\r\n\r\nOne example of this, was a challenge a client faced in how best to educate and support new leaders around the importance of non-verbal communication within their team.\r\n\r\nThe obvious choice for explaining non verbal cues was for users to see it in action, and so we decided to produce a series of films to showcase these. The use of film in learning content is nothing new, so why use this as an example?\r\n\r\nWe worked with the Royal Academy of Dramatic Arts (RADA) ‘In Business’ team, to provide talented actors to help bring to life the subtle non verbal cues and tone of voice that form the majority of team interactions in the workplace. Each film illustrated a leadership scenario in a quirky, real-world vignette that a newly transition leader could related to. The assistance of RADA helped add a level of gravitas and understanding to the messaging, whilst at the same time maintaining the users attention through a light hearted style and quality production values.\r\n\r\nBy pairing emotive, engaging rich media content with direct, practical information, we helped our intended audience enjoy the experience and retain the information.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"module module--16-9 module--video module--nozoom module--visible\" style=\"margin:50px 0px 50px 0px\">\r\n						<div class=\"ratio\">\r\n							<iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/139011465?color=FF406A&amp;title=0&amp;byline=0&amp;portrait=0 \" webkitallowfullscreen=\"\" mozallowfullscreen=\"\" allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"100%\" width=\"100%\"></iframe>\r\n							\r\n						</div>\r\n					</div>\r\n\r\n\"These videos smashed all previous records – for click-through’s and video plays – doubling the previous highest ever. Congrats.\"\r\nShane Samarawikrema, BP\r\n\r\nFor more information about these videos and the wider project, please visit: <a href=\"http://wearetilt.com/work/bp-fll/\">http://wearetilt.com/work/bp-fll/</a>\r\n'),(7796,704,'_main_content_area','field_5629ec918a334'),(7803,631,'_wp_old_slug','elwoods-arc'),(7808,707,'header_image','633'),(7809,707,'_header_image','field_5629edc6a3424'),(7810,707,'standfirst_text','A young boy releases a cloud into a church and it builds to a storm. Elwood’s Ark traces the journey of the water we drink, back 13.8 billion years through time and space to the beginnings of the Universe, challenging our perceptions of religion and redemption.'),(7811,707,'_standfirst_text','field_5629ea6d8d729'),(7812,707,'image_1','634'),(7813,707,'_image_1','field_560ba235a1f37'),(7814,707,'image_2','635'),(7815,707,'_image_2','field_560ba25da1f38'),(7816,707,'image_3','636'),(7817,707,'_image_3','field_560ba272a1f39'),(7818,707,'image_4','637'),(7819,707,'_image_4','field_560ba279a1f3a'),(7820,707,'single_image',''),(7821,707,'_single_image','field_5629ea2db47b2'),(7822,707,'vimeo_id','138625045'),(7823,707,'_vimeo_id','field_5629e91cf9252'),(7824,707,'vimeo_id_two',''),(7825,707,'_vimeo_id_two','field_564b0ac8ebbf4'),(7826,707,'youtube_id',''),(7827,707,'_youtube_id','field_5629e94ef9253'),(7828,707,'_','field_5629e968f9254'),(7829,707,'main_content_area','Water is something that everyone can relate to. Yet we rarely think about where it comes from, and how far its ancient molecular cocktail has travelled, to be here with us in this small moment - or how it will exist long after we\'re gone. For Elwood\'s Ark, we wanted to create a short film that would approach the subject of water’s journey, and our fragile relationship with it, putting into perspective human existence in the vastness of time and space.\r\n\r\nThe towering brick arches and Noah\'s Ark-like appearance of St Bartholomew\'s church seemed a fitting setting for this story. It is an ever-present feature of our daily lives at Tilt - a vast solitary relic from a flattened Victorian neighbourhood that is now the heart of Brighton\'s blooming digital community. The huge interior – the largest nave in England - offered an amazing opportunity in which to grow a digital lightening storm, released from the hands of a child.\r\n\r\nThe film is shot in 6k RED cinema to obtain film industry standard image quality at high frame rates (for slow motion). We played with FumeFX and Elementacular for Maya to produce realistic evolving 3d rain clouds, used Optical Flares in AfterEffects to give it an epic anamorphic look, and graded the footage with DaVinci Resolve.'),(7830,707,'_main_content_area','field_5629ec918a334'),(7835,710,'_edit_lock','1460673242:1'),(7836,710,'_edit_last','1'),(7837,711,'_wp_attached_file','2016/03/header.jpg'),(7838,711,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:1280;s:6:\"height\";i:540;s:4:\"file\";s:18:\"2016/03/header.jpg\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:5:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:18:\"header-150x150.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}s:6:\"medium\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:18:\"header-300x127.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:300;s:6:\"height\";i:127;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}s:12:\"medium_large\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:18:\"header-768x324.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:768;s:6:\"height\";i:324;s:9:\"mime-type\