dit_last','10'),(9493,845,'image_1',''),(9494,845,'_image_1','field_560ba235a1f37'),(9495,845,'image_2',''),(9496,845,'_image_2','field_560ba25da1f38'),(9497,845,'image_3',''),(9498,845,'_image_3','field_560ba272a1f39'),(9499,845,'image_4',''),(9500,845,'_image_4','field_560ba279a1f3a'),(9501,845,'main_content_area','‘User experience design’ is of course a different notion, featuring an amalgamation of processes and methodologies that are utilised to gather a definitive user-centric approach that greatly influences the way we design and build things. Without exploring this too much (because my blog posts are universally agreed to be too long), I want to talk about how strong ‘user experiences’ come about at Tilt, and the fundamental rule we follow to achieve this.\r\n\r\nA day in the life of a Tilter closely resembles the scene in Home Alone where everyone is getting ready for the airport. This is probably because a lot of what we offer involves a lot of different people. Our web and interactive products especially. To create a solid user experience for a FTSE100 brand’s internal communications project, we will involve strategists, designers, developers, motion designers, filmmakers and project managers. Whilst we are all responsible for our individual niche and the project manager is responsible for the health of the project. The over encompassing ‘user experience’ is developed through a sort of ethos heavily based on team accountability. We all need to deliver on our individual task that when combined brings a successful product. \r\n\r\nAs Tilt adapts to the demands of an ever-changing digital industry with ever-changing process, we remind ourselves that the basic rules never change. \r\n\r\n1) Listen and appreciate other people’s knowledge - I’ve never met a polymath, I’ve met a few people who consider themselves polymaths. But the best way to develop a product that has been considered from all angles, is to listen and consider all opinions. There is no proof that Da Vinci did all that sh*t on his own. \r\n\r\n2) Place more emphasis on content strategy and planning - 99.95% of user’s are on your site for the content - the other 0.05% is you looking at your own website, possibly your nan depending on the pride you take in your work. Place time and budget in getting everyone talking about it early on. The UX team at Tilt believe information architecture & wayfinding are the foundations of a solid online platform. \r\n\r\n3) Use a UX practise that suits your culture and organisation - As noted earlier, the industry is ever changing, meaning there is no conclusively relevant ‘way of doing things’. Company leaders want to convince clients and competitors alike that their design practise is the one truest to the original premise, unless you’re Don Norman, that’s probably not the case. Find a way of working that utilises your employee’s skill-sets.\r\n\r\nIn our case, that’s working as a team. \r\n'),(9502,845,'_main_content_area','field_5629ec918a334'),(9503,845,'single_image',''),(9504,845,'_single_image','field_5629ea2db47b2'),(9505,845,'header_image',''),(9506,845,'_header_image','field_5629edc6a3424'),(9507,845,'standfirst_text','The User Experience approach at Tilt is a mysterious force - one sketched in the lab of optimism, forged in the pits of despair (erm, hard-graft). Outside of our walls it’s a topic that spawns great debate and many a twitter feud between middle-age ladies and gentlemen of the industry. For us, put perhaps naively, ‘UX’ for us is the reaction to great product design. '),(9508,845,'_standfirst_text','field_5629ea6d8d729'),(9509,845,'vimeo_id',''),(9510,845,'_vimeo_id','field_5629e91cf9252'),(9511,845,'vimeo_id_two',''),(9512,845,'_vimeo_id_two','field_564b0ac8ebbf4'),(9513,845,'youtube_id',''),(9514,845,'_youtube_id','field_5629e94ef9253'),(9515,845,'_','field_5629e968f9254'),(9516,844,'image_1','862'),(9517,844,'_image_1','field_560ba235a1f37'),(9518,844,'image_2','864'),(9519,844,'_image_2','field_5